\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\b\f0\fs22 President\rquote s Report\~\b0\line for 2015 AGM North Queensland Ensembles Inc.\~\line\fs20\line The Barrier Reef Orchestra is in a sound financial position with concert attendance and revenue from tickets up for 2013.\~\line\line The Orchestra has performed on six occasions over the last 12 months. This included a children\rquote s concert at Riverway featuring music from Harry Potter and Peter and the Wolf. The concert was well received by the audience and the Orchestra got into the mood by dressing up appropriately for their musical characters.\~\line\line Masterworks conducted by Mark Sheills, featuring the 2013 Australian Concerto and Vocal Competition winner was performed in September with a follow up performance in Burdekin. \line\line Last Night of the Proms was performed in November and conducted by Richard McIntyre with the audience joining in with antics. \par
The new year began with a successful season launch at the Pier Restaurant which featured our new harp much to the enjoyment of those present. The Mayor of Townsville, Councillor Jenny Hill, officially launched the 2015 season and spoke of the importance of the Barrier Reef Orchestra to Townsville. Not long after that was Sounds of Romance conducted by Raymond Yong. There was an issue of parking at the venue but this was taken up with the Council.\line\line The Orchestra was invited to open the Townsville Arts Awards with a cameo performance with music from Frozen much to the audiences\rquote  pleasure, particularly with the AV accompaniment. The Barrier Reef Orchestra will conduct the second Conducting Workshop at the end of May as it was so successful in 2013.\~\line\line For the rest of the year there is our support to the AFCM concert, our World Music Concert commissioned by the Civic Theatre (a first for BRO), support to DanceNorth with their Twilight performances and lastly a Musical Feast for November.\~\line\line To make all of this happen there is a dynamic and committed committee working busily to bring this all together. I thank them all for their magnificent work. Many thanks to our major sponsor the Townsville City Council, our generous benefactors and to the Orchestra Manager Sally Frewen-Lord who has found time to run a survey for the musicians to get accommodating feedback. \line\line Jeff Nielsen has reworked our website and taken great steps forward in producing a functional and relevant website. Jeff will no longer be operating our website, but we thank you for your continued efforts. Marking the 15\super th\nosupersub  anniversary of the Barrier Reef Orchestra an introduction of life members will be added to the website. \line\line The Barrier Reef Orchestra has taken the opportunity to be directly involved with the development of the TPAC proposal. It is necessary to support all of the arts organisations to promote the need for more performance spaces in Townsville. Simon has injected himself into this project with the usual eye for detail while keeping appraised of the macro developments in Townsville. Thanks Simon for your energy and incisive views on this important project.\~\line\line The 15th anniversary year of BRO has been marked by several approaches to the Orchestra to perform in support of other arts organisations. This is seen as a sign of confidence others see in our Orchestra. Along with acceptance of the Barrier Reef Orchestra as Townsville\rquote s resident cultural cornerstone to orchestral music. A fitting milestone for the 15th year of the Barrier Reef Orchestra.\~\par
